I posted the following 5 years ago today: “For the last 20 years, I’ve spent every dime I’ve earned to further research, find and cultivate the best recording equipment ever made.  This journey illuminated an inevitable dream whereby I would one day open a commercial studio where like minded artists would record in my sanctuary, under my terms, with no computers or commensurate digital objectives. It is with great pleasure that I announce that this dream has come true.

When I began making music in ‘96, with a sampler and a cassette recorder, I learned that in order to be the best artist possible, I had to teach myself how to play instruments and record in a way that exemplified the classic breaks I adored.  With no money, and an overabundance of passion, I spent every cent on analog equipment and education: I read books on linear recording while simultaneously studying law; I asked the right questions and created a life with no regard of how others saw my nebulous journey.  Essentially, I started proving to myself that unfettered self-belief, coupled with perseverance, is the key.

With that perspective, I believed in one day developing my own sonic palette:  a musical theory based on studying vinyl in order to develop a new kind of music and sound. But with my crazy dreams, I didn’t know that I could surpass what I thought was already impossible.  I never thought I’d develop the ability to write music for orchestras and record orchestras in my own commercial studio, on my own analog tape, with my own antiquated equipment, with my own musical theory, for my own audience. This accomplishment may never be memorialized with a golden statue, but it has been memorialized in seeing how this move has pushed me beyond what i thought was possible.  It’s tangible elevation through continued self investment and unrelenting confidence.  From the sampler to the symphony, from the bedroom to the commercial magnetic recording facility, I’m happy to announce that my career has just begun.  It’s official, the new Linear Labs Studio is here.  This is life changing for me, my friends, my family and our future as artists.  Visit www.linearlabsmusic.com/studio for more. Thank you.

Just wanted to remind people that there is a viable and cheaper alternative to a Rhodes. This is the Pianet. Such a beautiful electric piano. 

Early Pianets were used on a number of hit recordings from the 1960s and 1970s, including "She's Not There" by The Zombies; "Louie Louie" by The Kingsmen; "Summer in the City" by The Lovin' Spoonful; "I Am the Walrus", "Getting Better", "The Night Before", "Tell Me What You See", "You Like Me Too Much" by The Beatles; "This Guy's in Love With You" by Herb Alpert; "These Eyes" by The Guess Who; and "Joy to the World" by Three Dog Night. In the glam rock era, the Pianet was used by Bryan Ferry on the first few Roxy Music albums, for instance featuring prominently in their hit Editions of You. It was a staple of the "classic lineup" sound of Curved Air (1970-1972), featuring prominently on their first 3 albums, played by both guitarist/keyboardist Francis Monkman and violinist Darryl Way. The 1972–74 lineup of progressive rock pioneers King Crimson used a pair of Pianets in live performance, played both by the group's violinist David Cross, and the guitarist, Robert Fripp[1]. Tony Banks of Genesis used one prominently on the group's first four albums, as a lead instrument through a homemade fuzz box and to simulate piano sounds onstage.

There is no debate. It’s really about what works better for your own music. You should know your sound and execute that…use the best tools to accomplish your goal. 

For me…I can’t make my type of music digitally. This is why I’ve put so much time into studying analog gear. 

Don’t get into analog unless you are willing to put in the work. It’s like having a vintage car that you must take care of…but the rewards are everlasting. Feel free to hit me if you have any questions.

The Baldwin electric harpsichord is truly unique. Well built and very inspiring. 

Famously heard on “Because,” the mournful second cut on side two of The Beatles’ album Abbey Road, this electric harpsichord was used extensively throughout the psychedelic ’60s. Popularized by Baroque revivalists and bands like The Doors, the Beach Boys and the Grateful Dead, the instrument was produced in very small numbers—with only 500 units remaining in existence today. Essentially consisting of an acoustic harpsichord, turbocharged by an electric guitar’s pick-up system, the electric harpsichord is definitely special. 

#studio #analog #harpsichord #recordingstudio #baldwin #music #beatles

I never get tired of this album. Very slept on and ahead of the times. Here is some info on James Mason: 

In the late 70s, James Mason decided to move on from being Roy Ayers' ace guitar player and make a solo record on the jazz label Chiaroscuro recruiting the talents of  Narada Michael Walden on drums and Gene Torres on bass.  1977's Rhythm of Life is a sophisticated soul jazz gem.  The album makes great use of new technology of the time, manufacturing memorable synth grooves over the vocal talents of Clarice Taylor.  At the time, the album was too funky for jazz stations and too jazzy for soul stations, hence it faded into obscurity until it was revitalized in the 80s acid jazz scene in the UK. The most well known cut is  the only single "Sweet Power Your Embrace" which reminds me of a tighter / more uptempo version of a Lonnie Liston Smith tune... airy and funky.  The track "Free" unveils Mason's Roy Ayers' jazz funk influence and "Slick City" is a happy jazz funker anchored by a smooth Rhodes groove.  Mason never went on to release another official album. 

#jazz #royayers #music #funk #vinyl

If you suffer from writers block, it’s because you have not opened up enough pathways for creation. It’s this science of repetition that alleviates the stress of having no ideas. Practice finishing songs. Most people start and then quickly stop after becoming fatigued. Train yourself to endure the pain of completing your ideas and this will help you in deterring writers block.

Fashion is important…it’s an escape from reality while also serving as a testament to one’s reality.  For me, clothes are never a frivolity.  There is purpose.  It’s like studying a crime scene and pulling out all the facts. It ain’t about who can afford the gear…it’s about who can assemble the illest public performance. Yes…style is performance and you have to have the eye to be a great performer and see a great performance. 

I say this all to say that it’s an honor to have scored an icon piece, with my bro @alishaheed, for a brand that has allowed me to find myself through fashion: @ralphlauren Ever since I was young, me and my boys rocked Ralph above all other brands as it exemplified something special for our Hip Hop subculture. It was our combination of street culture and aspirational clothing in an attempt to separate ourselves from the rest…in a way, it was a culture repurposing another for the purpose of establishing a new identity. That’s fashion y’all. 

Happy Black History month! By the way, if you are a Lo Head, check out these two on YouTube:

Delfonics: “Stop and Look”
Souls of Mischief: “There is only now”

Lastly, what is your favorite Lo piece and are you still collecting?

Every year we work around the clock to bring you rare and special experiences. It is with great honor and joy that we announce a six city US tour with @hermetopascoal aka O Bruxo (the wizard)!

There is good reason beyond his Gandalf-like appearance; Hermeto is a Brazilian legend. He has worked with the greatest of the greats, such as: @miltonbitucanascimento, @timmaia.oficial, @elisregina, @caetanoveloso, @gilbertogil and countless others. He first gained public attention in 1971 after performing and recording with @milesdavis on the Live/Evil album, of which Miles said, “Hermeto is one of the most important musicians on the planet.”

Pascoal uses nature as a basis for his compositions and often makes music with unconventional objects such as teapots, children's toys, and animals, as well as keyboards, button accordions, melodica, saxophones, guitars, flutes, voices, various brass and folkloric instruments.

Get ready and expect the unexpected! Tickets go on sale Friday March 17th and can be purchased via the links on jazzisdead.com/concerts.

The Adrian Younge challenge: For 30 days, pick up an instrument and spend 3hrs a day unlocking the true artist within. 

Today’s topic is vulnerability. Don’t be afraid to expose yourself because your journey is beautiful. It’s inspiring and magnetic. With discipline, you will only become better and prove to yourself that there is no better version of yourself, fully realized. 

If you need any advice or help with better understanding vulnerability, listen to my catalog. I never had formal training in school…I read books, asked questions, and had confidence. I never care about messing up because I’m human. Mistakes are beautiful as you are as good as your last recording. I’m not even where I will be, and when I listen to my older recordings, I am happy to see my growth. This is vulnerability. Be ok with impressing only yourself. Don’t care about props or accolades. Embrace vulnerability and become a champion. 

@linearlabsmusic @jazzisdead 

#adrianyoungechallenge #recordingstudio #inspire #create #instruments #fender #learn #vulnerability #inspiration #goals

Recording tip of the day: Essentially, it really doesn't matter how good you play your instrument. What matters the most is having the ability to create and complete a compelling composition. This is because the true appreciation of art is not necessarily academic; it's emotional. 

Don’t be afraid of making mistakes in front of others. It’s part of the process. Be vulnerable and allow others to watch your ascension. This is my daily routine.

About a year ago, I got a call from my agent asking whether I wanted to score a documentary science series for PBS…a science series? I always loved to watch these docs but never thought about scoring one…mainly because the music isn’t usually that hip..but anyways, I said I’d check it out. I watched the sizzle and I knew instantly that I had to be involved. It’s a science series unlike anything I’ve seen before…i guess it’s more like a series made for me with a particular cultural POV….and they let me score the series in a way that felt right….straight hip hop. 

The show is called Human Footprint and explores who we humans are as a species by looking at the ways we transform the planet. 

Episode 3: “Man’s Best Friend” airs tonight on @PBS! If you missed the first few episodes, you can stream #HumanFootprintPBS now on the @PBS App!

Episode 6 of Human Footprint “Ground Below” airs on PBS tomorrow night, August 9 at 9/8 ct.

This episode is very important: In an episode that hits close to home, Shane explores the history and science of cotton. A prehistoric coastline from North Carolina to Texas laid the foundation for a crop that re-shaped our history, our culture, and even our DNA. 

You will be surprised how much  cotton has integrally changed the way we see each other. I don’t want to give away too many details, but it is eye opening in regards to race relations in America and throughout the world. 

Lastly, I was honored to be featured as the composer for this incredible series as well as an expert on the etiology of black music in America. 

Please tune in and let us know your thoughts tonight. It’s a heavy one.  @the_artform_studio @linearlabsmusic @pbs

Recording tip of the day: You should view pro audio equipment as instruments. They are the color behind your sound and will impact the listener just as much as your composition. Sometimes, running your sound through something people consider “wack” actually makes it more interesting and vice versa. 

For example, when you listen to some of the greatest hip hop samples, the composition isn’t always the greatest…however, the recording methods on these samples are so interesting that they work, regardless of what was initially written. 

Do you know any examples of great hip hop samples that were more based on the “sound” of the sample opposed to the greatness of the samples “composition?” Share your thoughts.

Many years ago, I quit my 9-5 and was determined to make it as an artist. Becoming a professional artist was a dream, but there were so many obstacles that got in the way. Money was the biggest one, until I realized that insolvency wouldn’t kill me…it should fuel me. At this point, I spent everyday working on my craft because I truly believed I was dope…it’s just that nobody knew yet. 

My practice of waking up around 5am to “work for myself” really took form at this point. I began dressing differently because my clothes reflected a new state of mind: “I am the employer and the employee. As the employer I set my own standards and as the employee I would work relentlessly.” A new sense of discipline was born. 

I still wake up around 5am and put on that suit to go into work because I’m still dreaming. Nowadays, people don’t really ask me why I wear a suit everyday because it became part of my image over the years.  Nevertheless, I’m here to tell you that it’s still part of the discipline. 

The discipline is the key to unlocking the door to the professional artist within. Do what it takes to find value in yourself and use your obstacles to fuel your passion. Create ways that work for you and no one else…take yourself seriously because if you don’t…why should anyone else? 

@linearlabsmusic @jazzisdead

As we wrap up Series 2 of our catalog, we are filled with gratitude. There were plenty of highlights and spectacular moments such as @henryfranklin_theskipper winning an #NAACP spirit award with @adrianyounge and @alishaheed and our first ever #jazzisdead Summit in #SãoPaulo.  We will never forget the honor of hosting maestro @arthurverocai_ on his first ever US tour that landed on @cbschicago. 2023 has brought us far too many life changing moments  to name them all in this thread. 

We did have our share of lows when we lost alumni @ivancontimamao and @joao_donato Two of the greatest to ever do it in any genre, region or language and two of the sweetest people the earth ever birthed. 

Every day we are reminded to do our best to not only be present in the moment, but to also never take that moment for granted. It’s a great honor and privilege to have a seat at the table. We vow to continue our musical mission as we have huge news for you in the coming weeks. There will be big changes, but same flyness. 

We wish you all a happy new year! Be safe out there and love on the ones you love. - #jazzisdead
